The next Biennial should be in 2020 and will draw from the following creative sources:

Annie Leibovitz: Claire’s World, Mountain View, California;

The environment, the environment, environmental justice, and environmental solidarity. The first show will be an interactive experience, and will receive the first edition’s $10,000 prize.The second exhibition will be themed “Freedom of Nature” and will feature writing by the artist Kunstmuseum Stuttgart, Germany. The third will be an exhibition about the ecological crisis and its relation to the ongoing global war on terror, the fourth will be a series of works that examine ecological conflict and the ecological crisis in relation to contemporary life. The fifth and final exhibition will be a presentation of work by artist Teju Cole. The artist will take the stage at a time when communication, production, and art are becoming more and more intertwined and when environmental justice is being actively promoted and implemented. “We thought that this was the right moment to be more visible and more engaged in this new generation, to engage people who are not already familiar with her work,” said collaborator Suellen Cervetto
